WEBVTT

1
00:00:44.169 --> 00:00:46.092
Everyone is born,

2
00:00:46.255 --> 00:00:48.599
but not everyone
is born the same.

3
00:00:48.757 --> 00:00:52.978
Some will grow to be butchers or
bakers or candlestick makers.

4
00:00:53.136 --> 00:00:56.811
Some will only be really
good at making Jell-O salad.

5
00:00:56.974 --> 00:01:01.024
One way or another, though,
every human being is unique,

6
00:01:01.186 --> 00:01:03.530
for better or for worse.

7
00:01:04.898 --> 00:01:07.111
Most parents believe their
children are the most

8
00:01:07.135 --> 00:01:09.369
beautiful creatures ever
to Grace the planet.

9
00:01:09.695 --> 00:01:11.572
Others take a less
emotional approach.

10
00:01:11.738 --> 00:01:13.661
- What a waste of time.
- And painful.

11
00:01:13.824 --> 00:01:16.543
And expensive. $9.25
for a bar of soap?

12
00:01:16.702 --> 00:01:19.797
Well, I had to take a
shower, Harry. $5000?

13
00:01:19.955 --> 00:01:23.004
I'm not paying it. What are they
gonna do, repossess the kid?

14
00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:41.201
There's no way out.
Make a U-turn.

15
00:01:41.351 --> 00:01:42.398
All right.

16
00:01:48.859 --> 00:01:50.486
- Harry!
- All right.

17
00:01:51.486 --> 00:01:53.033
Harry!

18
00:01:53.238 --> 00:01:54.581
The Wormwood guy's back!

19
00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:56.413
Harry and
Zinnia Wormwood

20
00:01:56.575 --> 00:01:59.499
lived in a very nice neighborhood,
in a very nice house.

21
00:01:59.661 --> 00:02:02.460
But they were not really
very nice people.

22
00:02:12.758 --> 00:02:15.261
Get out of the
street, you little dodos!

23
00:02:21.808 --> 00:02:25.028
The Wormwoods were so
wrapped up in their own silly lives

24
00:02:25.187 --> 00:02:27.440
that they barely noticed
they had a daughter.

25
00:02:27.606 --> 00:02:29.825
Had they paid any
attention to her at all,

26
00:02:29.983 --> 00:02:33.328
they'd have realized she was a
rather extraordinary child.

27
00:02:33.487 --> 00:02:36.115
Oh, my gosh, Matilda,
now look what you did!

28
00:02:36.281 --> 00:02:38.409
They named her Matilda.

29
00:02:38.575 --> 00:02:41.920
You're supposed
to eat the spinach. Ooh!

30
00:02:51.046 --> 00:02:52.593
Babies!

31
00:02:52.756 --> 00:02:55.635
You're better off
raising tomatoes.

32
00:02:56.218 --> 00:02:57.891
By the
time she was 2,

33
00:02:58.053 --> 00:03:01.398
Matilda had learned what most
people learn in their early 30s.

34
00:03:01.556 --> 00:03:03.729
How to take care of herself.

35
00:03:06.978 --> 00:03:11.279
As time went by, she
developed a sense of style.

36
00:03:12.150 --> 00:03:14.903
Every morning, Matilda's brother,
Michael, went to school.

37
00:03:15.112 --> 00:03:16.284
Bye, Mom. Get out of here.

38
00:03:16.446 --> 00:03:19.416
Her father worked selling
used cars Make money.

39
00:03:19.574 --> 00:03:22.669
For unfair prices. And her
mother took off to play bingo.

40
00:03:22.828 --> 00:03:25.923
Soup's on the stove. Heat
it up if you get hungry.

41
00:03:26.123 --> 00:03:28.296
Matilda was left alone.

42
00:03:29.668 --> 00:03:31.215
That was how she liked it.

43
00:04:07.122 --> 00:04:11.377
By the time she was 4, Matilda
had read every magazine in the house.

44
00:04:11.918 --> 00:04:13.841
One night, she got
up her courage

45
00:04:14.004 --> 00:04:17.725
and asked her father for something
she desperately wanted.

46
00:04:17.883 --> 00:04:20.682
A book? What do you
want a book for?

47
00:04:20.886 --> 00:04:22.183
To read.

48
00:04:22.345 --> 00:04:25.599
To read? Why would you wanna read
when you got the television set

49
00:04:25.766 --> 00:04:27.860
sitting right in front of you?

50
00:04:28.685 --> 00:04:30.835
There's nothing you can
get from a book that

51
00:04:30.859 --> 00:04:33.031
you can't get from a
television faster.

52
00:04:33.190 --> 00:04:34.942
Get out of the way!

53
00:04:36.050 --> 00:04:39.171
Matilda already knew that she
was somewhat different from her family.

54
00:04:40.363 --> 00:04:42.786
She saw that whatever she
needed in this world,

55
00:04:42.949 --> 00:04:44.951
she'd have to get herself.

56
00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:47.128
Bye. Ciao.

57
00:04:47.287 --> 00:04:50.166
There's fish fingers
in the microwave.

58
00:04:53.043 --> 00:04:56.092
The next morning,
after her parents left,

59
00:04:56.254 --> 00:04:58.677
Matilda set off in
search of a book.

60
00:05:37.587 --> 00:05:40.215
Where are the children's
books, please?

61
00:05:40.382 --> 00:05:42.100
In that room right over there.

62
00:05:42.259 --> 00:05:45.388
Would you like me to pick you out
one with lots of pictures in it?

63
00:05:46.096 --> 00:05:49.350
No, thank you. I'm
sure I can manage.

64
00:06:05.532 --> 00:06:09.036
From then on, every day,
as soon as her mother went to bingo,

65
00:06:09.327 --> 00:06:12.922
Matilda walked the 10
blocks to the library

66
00:06:14.040 --> 00:06:16.919
and devoured one
book after another.

67
00:06:21.089 --> 00:06:23.433
When she finished all
the children's books,

68
00:06:23.592 --> 00:06:26.641
she started wandering around
in search of something else.

69
00:06:26.803 --> 00:06:29.727
Mrs. Phelps, who had been
watching her with fascination

70
00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:31.358
for the past few weeks,

71
00:06:31.516 --> 00:06:34.520
offered Matilda some valuable
library information.

72
00:06:34.686 --> 00:06:37.530
You know, you could have
your very own library card.

73
00:06:37.689 --> 00:06:40.067
And then you could
take books home

74
00:06:40.233 --> 00:06:43.237
and you wouldn't have
to walk here every day.

75
00:06:43.403 --> 00:06:45.576
You could take as
many as you like.

76
00:06:45.739 --> 00:06:48.117
That would be wonderful.

77
00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:54.255
So Matilda's strong,
young mind continued to grow,

78
00:06:54.414 --> 00:06:57.167
nurtured by the voices
of all those authors

79
00:06:57.334 --> 00:06:59.837
who had sent their books
out into the world

80
00:07:00.003 --> 00:07:02.973
like ships onto the sea.

81
00:07:10.931 --> 00:07:15.402
These books gave Matilda a
hopeful and comforting message.

82
00:07:15.685 --> 00:07:17.687
You are not alone.

83
00:07:38.041 --> 00:07:39.543
Any packages come today?

84
00:07:42.003 --> 00:07:43.721
Where did all this come from?

85
00:07:44.214 --> 00:07:45.887
The library.

86
00:07:46.049 --> 00:07:50.225
The library? You've never set foot in
a library. You're only 4 years old.

87
00:07:50.512 --> 00:07:51.764
Six and a half.

88
00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:53.557
You're 4. Six and a half.

89
00:07:53.723 --> 00:07:56.067
If you were 6 and a half,
you'd be in school already.

90
00:07:56.226 --> 00:07:58.069
I want to be in school.
I told you

91
00:07:58.228 --> 00:08:01.698
I was supposed to start school in
September. You wouldn't listen.

92
00:08:02.357 --> 00:08:04.576
Get up. Get UP!

93
00:08:05.318 --> 00:08:08.037
Get out here. Give
me that book.

94
00:08:10.323 --> 00:08:13.748
Dearest pie, how old is Matilda?
Four

95
00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:16.834
I'm 6 and a half, Mommy.
Five, then.

96
00:08:17.038 --> 00:08:19.416
I was 6 in August.
You're a liar.

97
00:08:19.791 --> 00:08:22.920
I wanna go to school. School!

98
00:08:23.086 --> 00:08:26.340
Out of the question. Who would be
here to sign for the packages?

99
00:08:26.506 --> 00:08:29.601
We can't leave valuable packages
sitting out on the doorstep.

100
00:08:29.843 --> 00:08:32.437
Now, go watch TV
like a good kid.

101
00:08:32.595 --> 00:08:35.974
You know, sometimes I think there's
something wrong with that girl.

102
00:08:36.141 --> 00:08:38.690
Hm. Tell me about it. Mm.

103
00:08:39.227 --> 00:08:40.695
Hey, dip-face,

104
00:08:40.854 --> 00:08:44.279
have a marshmallow. Have
another marshmallow, dip-face!

105
00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:46.743
Dip-face!

106
00:08:54.617 --> 00:08:57.291
Sometimes Matilda
longed for a friend.

107
00:08:57.454 --> 00:09:01.084
Someone like the kind,
courageous people in her books.

108
00:09:01.249 --> 00:09:04.628
It occurred to her that like
talking dragons and princesses

109
00:09:04.794 --> 00:09:10.426
with hair long enough to climb, such
people might exist only in storybooks.

110
00:09:10.633 --> 00:09:14.354
But Matilda was about to discover
that she could be her own friend.

111
00:09:14.512 --> 00:09:17.391
That she had a kind of strength
she wasn't even aware of.

112
00:09:17.932 --> 00:09:20.526
I'm great! I'm incredible!

113
00:09:20.685 --> 00:09:23.154
Michael, pencil and
paper, in the kitchen.

114
00:09:23.313 --> 00:09:25.907
Did we sell some cars
today, honeydew?

115
00:09:26.066 --> 00:09:27.363
Did we!

116
00:09:27.525 --> 00:09:29.448
Does that mean I can
get that new TV?

117
00:09:29.611 --> 00:09:32.785
Yeah. Son, one day you're gonna
have to earn your own living.

118
00:09:32.947 --> 00:09:35.041
It's time you learned
the family business.

119
00:09:35.200 --> 00:09:37.623
Sit down. Write this down.

120
00:09:38.244 --> 00:09:43.125
All right. The first car your
brilliant father sold cost $320.

121
00:09:43.291 --> 00:09:46.966
I sold it for $1158.

122
00:09:47.128 --> 00:09:49.677
The second one cost $512.

123
00:09:49.839 --> 00:09:55.016
I sold it for $2269.

124
00:09:55.178 --> 00:09:57.522
Wait, Dad, you're going
too fast. Just write.

125
00:09:57.680 --> 00:10:03.028
The third cost $68.
I sold it for $999.

126
00:10:03.186 --> 00:10:07.191
And the fourth cost $1100.

127
00:10:07.357 --> 00:10:13.285
I sold it for 7839
big American boffos.

128
00:10:13.446 --> 00:10:15.949
Harry! What was my
profit for the day?

129
00:10:16.116 --> 00:10:20.337
Could you repeat the
last one...? $10,265.

130
00:10:23.039 --> 00:10:25.383
Check it if you
don't believe me.

131
00:10:29.796 --> 00:10:31.844
You're a little cheat.
You saw the paper.

132
00:10:32.006 --> 00:10:33.679
From all the way over here?

133
00:10:35.218 --> 00:10:37.141
Are you being smart with me?

134
00:10:38.805 --> 00:10:41.486
If you're being smart with me, young
lady, you're gonna be punished.

135
00:10:41.599 --> 00:10:43.897
Punished for being smart?

136
00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:46.028
For being a smart aleck.

137
00:10:46.396 --> 00:10:49.991
When a person is bad, that person
has to be taught a lesson.

138
00:10:50.150 --> 00:10:52.073
Person? Get up!

139
00:10:52.569 --> 00:10:54.537
Get up.
Harry Wormwood

140
00:10:54.696 --> 00:10:56.949
had unintentionally
given his daughter

141
00:10:57.115 --> 00:10:59.868
the first practical
advice she could use.

142
00:11:00.034 --> 00:11:02.662
He meant to say, "When
a child is bad."

143
00:11:02.829 --> 00:11:05.457
Instead he said, "When
a person is bad."

144
00:11:05.623 --> 00:11:09.127
And thereby introduced
a revolutionary idea

145
00:11:09.294 --> 00:11:12.468
that children could
punish their parents.

146
00:11:14.299 --> 00:11:16.677
Only when they deserved
it, of course.

147
00:12:36.089 --> 00:12:38.467
Michael,
come into my room.

148
00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:42.637
What?

149
00:12:42.804 --> 00:12:46.684
My boy, today's the day I take you
to the shop. What do you say?

150
00:12:46.849 --> 00:12:49.068
I don't know. What
do you say, Dad?

151
00:12:49.227 --> 00:12:51.696
I say appearance is
nine-tenths of the law.

152
00:12:51.854 --> 00:12:53.902
People don't buy a
car, they buy me.

153
00:12:54.065 --> 00:12:57.035
Which is why I personally take
such pride in my appearance.

154
00:12:57.193 --> 00:13:00.663
Well-oiled hair, clean
shaved, snappy suit.

155
00:13:00.822 --> 00:13:03.951
Now, run along and get ready for
a big day of learning, kid. Heh.

156
00:13:04.117 --> 00:13:06.245
It's gonna be a big
day of learning too.

157
00:13:06.411 --> 00:13:09.881
There's a sucker born every minute.
We're gonna take them for all they got.

158
00:13:10.623 --> 00:13:12.216
Give me the cookies.

159
00:13:12.625 --> 00:13:14.172
Here.

160
00:13:20.008 --> 00:13:22.887
Okay, my boy, heir
to the throne.

161
00:13:23.052 --> 00:13:25.726
Today we diddle the customer.

162
00:13:25.972 --> 00:13:28.896
What's wrong with you?
What are you looking at?

163
00:13:29.392 --> 00:13:31.690
Lovekins, where's my breakfast?

164
00:13:31.853 --> 00:13:35.153
Here we are, my heartstrings.

165
00:13:36.607 --> 00:13:39.577
Snickerdoodle, what did
you do to your hair?

166
00:13:42.739 --> 00:13:44.366
My hair?

167
00:13:56.002 --> 00:13:58.755
Give me those things. Give me that.
Where are you going with those?

168
00:13:58.921 --> 00:14:01.265
Give me those. Get in the car.
Go on.

169
00:14:04.761 --> 00:14:06.479
Get in.
Dirty dealings,

170
00:14:07.972 --> 00:14:11.351
Like buying stolen car parts,
never stay secret for long.

171
00:14:11.517 --> 00:14:14.612
Especially when the
FBI gets involved.

172
00:14:20.860 --> 00:14:24.410
9:17, suspect exits domicile.

173
00:14:24.572 --> 00:14:26.449
I've got 9:18.

174
00:14:28.576 --> 00:14:30.294
9:17 is correct.

175
00:14:40.755 --> 00:14:44.635
Michael, one day all
this will be yours.

176
00:14:44.884 --> 00:14:46.511
This?

177
00:14:46.677 --> 00:14:49.806
See this junker?
I paid $100 for it.

178
00:14:49.972 --> 00:14:52.100
She's got 120,000 miles on her.

179
00:14:52.266 --> 00:14:55.190
Transmission shot,
bumpers have fallen off.

180
00:14:55.353 --> 00:14:57.276
What do I do with her? Hm?

181
00:14:59.232 --> 00:15:00.575
I sell her.

182
00:15:00.733 --> 00:15:03.202
We really should weld
these bumpers on,

183
00:15:03.361 --> 00:15:07.161
but that takes time,
equipment, money.

184
00:15:07.323 --> 00:15:10.827
So we use Super
Super Glue instead.

185
00:15:10.993 --> 00:15:13.371
Go ahead, put it on there.

186
00:15:13.621 --> 00:15:15.123
Won't it fall off?

187
00:15:15.289 --> 00:15:18.338
Definitely. Isn't
that dangerous?

188
00:15:18.501 --> 00:15:20.629
Not to me, okay?

189
00:15:20.795 --> 00:15:22.297
Transmission.

190
00:15:22.463 --> 00:15:26.684
The sawdust quiets the gears, and
lets the engine run as sweet as a nut

191
00:15:26.843 --> 00:15:29.346
for a couple of miles. Ha-ha-ha.
Daddy, that's cheating.

192
00:15:29.512 --> 00:15:33.016
Of course it's cheating. Nobody
ever got rich being honest.

193
00:15:33.182 --> 00:15:36.186
20 years ago, we could turn the
numbers back by hand. But...

194
00:15:36.352 --> 00:15:38.354
Here, take my hat.

195
00:15:38.688 --> 00:15:42.909
But the feds like to test the ingenuity
of the American businessman.

196
00:15:43.109 --> 00:15:44.656
Two-directional drill.

197
00:15:44.819 --> 00:15:47.288
You run it backwards,
the numbers go down.

198
00:15:47.447 --> 00:15:49.666
Watch the speedometer.

199
00:15:50.825 --> 00:15:52.372
Cool.

200
00:15:54.579 --> 00:15:55.626
See? Yeah.

201
00:15:55.788 --> 00:15:57.836
Daddy, you're a crook.

202
00:15:58.833 --> 00:16:01.131
What? This is illegal.

203
00:16:01.794 --> 00:16:03.341
Here, keep drilling.

204
00:16:05.131 --> 00:16:07.930
Do you make money?
Do you have a job?

205
00:16:08.092 --> 00:16:10.470
No, but don't people
need good cars?

206
00:16:10.636 --> 00:16:13.310
Can't you sell good cars, Dad?

207
00:16:14.056 --> 00:16:16.024
Listen, you little wiseacre.

208
00:16:16.184 --> 00:16:19.814
I'm smart, you're dumb. I'm big, you're
little. I'm right, you're wrong.

209
00:16:19.979 --> 00:16:22.232
And there's nothing
you can do about it.

210
00:16:34.994 --> 00:16:37.998
Harry, I won! I won!

211
00:16:38.164 --> 00:16:41.759
I hit the double bingo! Aah!

212
00:16:41.918 --> 00:16:45.343
Come on, everybody! I'm taking
you all to Café Le Ritz.

213
00:16:45.505 --> 00:16:47.382
Let me see the money.
Never mind.

214
00:16:47.548 --> 00:16:49.346
Double bingo, huh? Ooh.

215
00:16:49.634 --> 00:16:53.013
God, your hair looks awful.
I hope they let you in.

216
00:16:53.179 --> 00:16:55.181
They'll let me in.
Here's your hat, Daddy.

217
00:16:55.473 --> 00:16:57.225
Get in the car.

218
00:16:58.476 --> 00:16:59.944
Go on, get in.

219
00:17:02.146 --> 00:17:03.193
How much?

220
00:17:03.356 --> 00:17:05.279
It's for me to know
and you to find out.

221
00:17:11.197 --> 00:17:13.074
It's nice to go out sometimes.
Yeah.

222
00:17:13.241 --> 00:17:14.288
You never take us out.

223
00:17:14.450 --> 00:17:16.202
Of course I do. I took
you to the Flipper.

224
00:17:16.369 --> 00:17:18.713
- I don't remember any of the Flipper.
- The fish joint.

225
00:17:18.871 --> 00:17:20.965
You found that comb
in the bouillabaisse.

226
00:17:21.123 --> 00:17:23.125
Oh, yeah. I
like that joint.

227
00:17:23.626 --> 00:17:25.594
Bonjour. This way, please.

228
00:17:25.753 --> 00:17:27.255
Harry, take your hat off.

229
00:17:28.256 --> 00:17:29.849
I can't. This is a nice place.

230
00:17:30.007 --> 00:17:31.850
You can't wear a hat inside.

231
00:17:32.009 --> 00:17:33.135
I can't take it off.

232
00:17:33.302 --> 00:17:36.146
Harry, nobody cares what
your hair looks like.

233
00:17:36.305 --> 00:17:39.525
What's with this hat? I can't
get it off. I can't get it off.

234
00:17:41.018 --> 00:17:44.272
Just a minute. I'm gonna yank
this hat off. I'm pulling it.

235
00:17:46.774 --> 00:17:49.118
I think your head
swelled up really bad.

236
00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:54.540
You're pulling the skin!
You're such a baby! Stop it!

237
00:17:54.699 --> 00:17:57.168
Fibers are fused to the head!
Fibers are fused?

238
00:17:57.326 --> 00:18:00.250
What is that supposed to mean?
Give me that hat!

239
00:18:33.487 --> 00:18:35.865
I will not be the
figure of ridicule!

240
00:18:36.032 --> 00:18:38.251
I want respect, and
I want it now!

241
00:18:40.202 --> 00:18:42.955
I still don't see how you
glued your hat on, Harry.

242
00:18:43.122 --> 00:18:45.716
I mean, I know you say you
didn't, but obviously you did.

243
00:18:45.875 --> 00:18:48.344
I did not glue my
hat to my head.

244
00:18:48.502 --> 00:18:52.678
The hat shrunk, the fibers
fused to my hair. Ow.

245
00:18:52.882 --> 00:18:55.260
Baby, wait a minute.
I'm getting it now.

246
00:18:55.426 --> 00:18:57.224
I'm getting it. One more.

247
00:18:59.805 --> 00:19:01.352
Oh, my God.

248
00:19:10.691 --> 00:19:13.820
From now on, this family
does exactly what I say,

249
00:19:13.986 --> 00:19:16.409
when, exactly when, I say it!

250
00:19:16.572 --> 00:19:19.075
Here's your hat, Harry.
Give me that.

251
00:19:19.325 --> 00:19:21.168
And right now,

252
00:19:21.494 --> 00:19:24.714
we are eating dinner
and watching TV.

253
00:19:26.832 --> 00:19:30.587
Are you ready to get
sticky with Mickey?

254
00:19:32.004 --> 00:19:33.597
Shut your light off.

255
00:19:34.674 --> 00:19:36.768
I'm just giving it away!

256
00:19:36.926 --> 00:19:40.931
But for those idiots out there who don't
know how to play, here's how it goes.

257
00:19:41.097 --> 00:19:45.443
For each correct answer, they'll move
one step closer to our cube of cash.

258
00:19:45.601 --> 00:19:49.526
Once in our cube of cash, any money
that sticks to your gooey body,

259
00:19:49.689 --> 00:19:51.862
you get to take home.

260
00:19:54.819 --> 00:19:56.662
Hi, Dad.

261
00:19:56.821 --> 00:19:58.243
Are you in this family?

262
00:20:01.450 --> 00:20:03.293
Hello?

263
00:20:03.452 --> 00:20:06.046
Are you in this family?

264
00:20:09.041 --> 00:20:12.341
Dinnertime is family time. What
is this trash you're reading?

265
00:20:12.628 --> 00:20:14.801
It's not trash,
Daddy, it's lovely.

266
00:20:14.964 --> 00:20:17.217
It's called Moby Dick,
by Herman Melville.

267
00:20:18.134 --> 00:20:19.556
Moby what?

268
00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:26.022
This is filth! Trash! Here. It's
not mine! It's a library book.

269
00:20:26.183 --> 00:20:27.730
Trash!

270
00:20:27.893 --> 00:20:32.114
I'm fed up with all this reading! You're
a Wormwood, you start acting like one!

271
00:20:32.273 --> 00:20:33.616
Sit up and look at the TV.

272
00:20:33.774 --> 00:20:35.612
Producers are not
liable for any skin

273
00:20:35.636 --> 00:20:37.556
irritation that may result
from playing our game.

274
00:20:37.653 --> 00:20:39.781
Get real sticky and
get cash for free.

275
00:20:39.947 --> 00:20:43.247
All right, that's enough.
Let's get sticky!

276
00:21:20.905 --> 00:21:22.657
I didn't do it.

277
00:21:22.823 --> 00:21:25.667
Of course you didn't do
it, you little twit.

278
00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:28.333
I told you that
was a cheap set.

279
00:21:28.496 --> 00:21:32.217
It's not a cheap set,
it's a stolen set.

280
00:21:32.374 --> 00:21:34.092
Put your light on!

281
00:21:36.045 --> 00:21:37.092
Bummer.

282
00:21:37.254 --> 00:21:39.222
Was it magic
or coincidence?

283
00:21:39.381 --> 00:21:40.883
She didn't know.

284
00:21:41.050 --> 00:21:44.771
It is said that we humans use only
a tiny portion of our brains.

285
00:21:44.929 --> 00:21:48.433
Matilda might never have discovered
her own great strength of mind

286
00:21:48.599 --> 00:21:52.274
were it not for the events that
began on the very next day.

287
00:21:52.436 --> 00:21:54.859
I need a car,
inexpensive but reliable.

288
00:21:55.022 --> 00:21:57.696
Can you service me?
In a manner of speaking, yes.

289
00:21:57.858 --> 00:21:59.280
Welcome to Wormwood Motors.

290
00:21:59.443 --> 00:22:01.696
Harry Wormwood, owner,
founder, whatever.

291
00:22:01.862 --> 00:22:05.787
Agatha Trunchbull, principal,
Crunchem Hall Elementary School.

292
00:22:06.242 --> 00:22:09.746
I warn you, Sir, I want a tight
car, because I run a tight ship.

293
00:22:09.912 --> 00:22:13.837
Oh, yeah, huh? Well, uh... My
school is a model of discipline.

294
00:22:13.999 --> 00:22:17.094
Use the Rod, beat the
child," that's my motto.

295
00:22:17.253 --> 00:22:19.597
Terrific motto. You
have brats yourself?

296
00:22:19.755 --> 00:22:22.178
Yeah, I got a boy, Mikey,
and one mistake, Matilda.

297
00:22:22.341 --> 00:22:26.471
They're all mistakes, children. Filthy,
nasty things. Glad I never was one.

298
00:22:26.637 --> 00:22:30.062
Uh-huh. Well, since you're an educator,
I'm gonna make you a great deal.

299
00:22:30.224 --> 00:22:32.852
You had better.
Let's do business.

300
00:22:34.687 --> 00:22:36.189
Thank you.

301
00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:37.948
Enjoy it.

302
00:22:38.774 --> 00:22:41.197
Hey, you, you're going
to school. I am?

303
00:22:41.360 --> 00:22:43.203
First thing tomorrow.

304
00:22:43.654 --> 00:22:47.409
Yeah, yeah, okay, okay. You'll get
a real education at this place.

305
00:22:49.869 --> 00:22:54.045
Matilda had always wanted to
go to school because she loved to learn.

306
00:22:54.582 --> 00:22:57.836
She tried to imagine what her
new school would be like.

307
00:22:58.002 --> 00:22:59.062
Go ahead.

308
00:22:59.086 --> 00:22:59.803
Go ahead.

309
00:23:00.087 --> 00:23:03.136
She pictured a lovely
building surrounded by trees

310
00:23:03.299 --> 00:23:05.677
and flowers and swings.

311
00:23:07.928 --> 00:23:09.930
Well, there was a building

312
00:23:10.139 --> 00:23:11.812
and children.

313
00:23:11.974 --> 00:23:14.602
So regardless of what
Crunchem Hall looked like,

314
00:23:14.768 --> 00:23:16.486
she was happy to be there.

315
00:23:16.645 --> 00:23:17.988
Hey, wait up!

316
00:23:18.439 --> 00:23:22.489
After all, any school
is better than no school at all.

317
00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:24.657
Isn't it?

318
00:23:58.896 --> 00:24:00.273
You, detention.

319
00:24:06.612 --> 00:24:08.706
You're too small.
Grow up quicker!

320
00:24:11.933 --> 00:24:14.053
Heads up! Shoulders back!
Stomachs in! Stand straight.

321
00:24:14.078 --> 00:24:15.295
Hey-sorry.

322
00:24:15.454 --> 00:24:16.614
Detention for you.

323
00:24:16.664 --> 00:24:19.713
That's okay. It's much
better than being out there.

324
00:24:19.875 --> 00:24:21.172
Is that my teacher?

325
00:24:21.335 --> 00:24:23.758
No, that's the principal,
Miss Trunchbull.

326
00:24:23.921 --> 00:24:25.889
You've gotta be kidding.

327
00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:28.684
You squirts better skedaddle.
I'm not kidding.

328
00:24:28.842 --> 00:24:31.722
The Trunchbull likes to snap a whip
in there to see who's trying to hide.

329
00:24:31.887 --> 00:24:33.434
Stomach in!

330
00:24:34.139 --> 00:24:35.766
Change those socks! Too pink.

331
00:24:35.933 --> 00:24:37.526
I'm Matilda. Lavender.

332
00:24:38.143 --> 00:24:39.861
I'm Hortensia.
Hi.

333
00:24:40.145 --> 00:24:43.900
She doesn't really hit children
with that riding crop, does she?

334
00:24:44.066 --> 00:24:46.194
No, it's mostly for scare.

335
00:24:46.360 --> 00:24:48.078
What she does is worse.

336
00:24:48.237 --> 00:24:52.037
Like yesterday, in the second grade,
the Trunchbull makes a weekly visit

337
00:24:52.199 --> 00:24:56.500
to every classroom to show the teachers
a thing or two about handling kids.

338
00:24:56.662 --> 00:24:58.084
And Julius Rottwinkle ate

339
00:24:58.247 --> 00:25:01.126
- two M&M's during her lesson.
- And she caught him?

340
00:25:01.291 --> 00:25:02.918
Of course.

341
00:25:08.841 --> 00:25:12.141
Was Julius okay? After being
thrown out the window?

342
00:25:12.302 --> 00:25:15.727
Of course he wasn't okay. He
lived, if that's what you mean.

343
00:25:15.889 --> 00:25:18.733
The Trunchbull used to
be in the Olympics.

344
00:25:18.892 --> 00:25:22.112
Shot put, javelin, hammer throw.

345
00:25:22.271 --> 00:25:23.581
The hammer
throw is her specialty.

346
00:25:23.605 --> 00:25:27.109
So she does this all the time?
Better than being put in the choky.

347
00:25:27.276 --> 00:25:30.029
Choky?
Yeah, the choky.

348
00:25:30.195 --> 00:25:33.039
It's a tall, narrow hole
in the wall behind a door.

349
00:25:33.198 --> 00:25:36.042
You have to stand in a drippy
pipe with jagged edges.

350
00:25:36.201 --> 00:25:38.750
And the walls have broken
glass and nails sticking out.

351
00:25:38.912 --> 00:25:41.791
Get inside, you
festering ball of pus!

352
00:25:41.957 --> 00:25:44.460
- She puts kids in there?
- I've been in twice.

353
00:25:44.626 --> 00:25:46.845
Sometimes she leaves
you in there all day.

354
00:25:47.004 --> 00:25:49.803
- Didn't you tell your parents?
- They didn't believe me.

355
00:25:50.007 --> 00:25:52.351
I mean, would your
parents believe it?

356
00:25:52.509 --> 00:25:55.308
Sixty lines after school:
I must obey Miss Trunchbull."

357
00:25:55.888 --> 00:25:57.435
No.

358
00:25:57.598 --> 00:25:59.817
Out of my way.
Here she comes.

359
00:26:01.643 --> 00:26:05.819
Ahh, fresh meat.

360
00:26:12.488 --> 00:26:14.616
Amanda Thripp.

361
00:26:15.908 --> 00:26:17.330
Yes, Miss Trunchbull.

362
00:26:17.618 --> 00:26:20.337
What are those? What's
what, Miss Trunchbull?

363
00:26:20.579 --> 00:26:23.332
Hanging
down by your ears.

364
00:26:23.499 --> 00:26:25.001
You mean my pigtails?

365
00:26:26.543 --> 00:26:30.343
Are you a pig, Amanda?
No, Miss Trunchbull.

366
00:26:30.798 --> 00:26:33.517
Do I allow pigs in my school?

367
00:26:33.675 --> 00:26:36.929
My mommy thinks they're sweet.

368
00:26:37.262 --> 00:26:39.856
Your mommy is a twit!

369
00:26:41.350 --> 00:26:44.479
You'll chop those off before
school tomorrow or I will...

370
00:26:44.853 --> 00:26:46.230
But... But?!

371
00:26:46.396 --> 00:26:49.115
I don't... But? Did
you say "but"?

372
00:26:49.691 --> 00:26:51.034
What? Hammer throw.

373
00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:52.828
Definitely.

374
00:26:52.986 --> 00:26:55.034
I'll give you "but"!

375
00:27:04.957 --> 00:27:08.302
Good loft!
And excellent release.

376
00:27:12.339 --> 00:27:15.058
Think she'll make the fence?
Gonna be a close one.

377
00:27:36.446 --> 00:27:39.575
Quiet! Get to class before I
throw you all in the choky.

378
00:27:40.242 --> 00:27:41.960
Lavender.

379
00:27:42.119 --> 00:27:43.712
What's my teacher like?

380
00:27:44.163 --> 00:27:47.918
Run, run, run.
Faster! Get in.

381
00:27:48.292 --> 00:27:49.589
Quickly!

382
00:27:49.751 --> 00:27:51.719
But Matilda's
teacher, Miss Honey,

383
00:27:51.879 --> 00:27:53.881
was one of those
remarkable people

384
00:27:54.047 --> 00:27:57.927
who appreciates every single
child for who she or he is.

385
00:27:58.093 --> 00:28:00.095
I scooped these up
for you, Miss Honey.

386
00:28:00.262 --> 00:28:03.607
Oh, how lovely.
Thank you, Amanda.

387
00:28:03.891 --> 00:28:07.816
Okay, listen up, everybody. We
have a new student with us today.

388
00:28:07.978 --> 00:28:11.528
This is Matilda Wormwood. I'd like
you to sit over here with Lavender.

389
00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:14.489
Now, you all remember how scary
your first days at school were.

390
00:28:14.651 --> 00:28:16.881
So I'd like you to be
especially nice to

391
00:28:16.905 --> 00:28:19.157
Matilda and make her
feel welcome, all right?

392
00:28:19.323 --> 00:28:20.884
Could you get her
workbook for her, please?

393
00:28:20.908 --> 00:28:23.661
Yes, Miss Honey.
You can sit down.

394
00:28:24.328 --> 00:28:27.798
Miss Honey was a wonderful
teacher and a friend to everyone.

395
00:28:27.956 --> 00:28:31.301
But her life was not as simple
and beautiful as it seemed.

396
00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:34.304
Miss Honey had a
deep, dark secret.

397
00:28:34.463 --> 00:28:36.306
Though it caused
her great pain,

398
00:28:36.465 --> 00:28:39.560
she did not let it interfere
with her teaching.

399
00:28:40.427 --> 00:28:43.476
Well, Matilda, you've
come on a very good day,

400
00:28:43.639 --> 00:28:47.143
because we're going to review
everything that we've learned so far.

401
00:28:47.420 --> 00:28:50.621
Now, it's all right if you don't understand
any of this because you're brand-new.

402
00:28:50.646 --> 00:28:53.820
But if you do know an answer,
just raise your hand. Okay?

403
00:28:54.191 --> 00:28:57.161
All right. We've been working
on our two-times tables.

404
00:28:57.319 --> 00:28:59.413
Would anyone like
to demonstrate?

405
00:29:00.781 --> 00:29:02.078
Okay.

406
00:29:02.241 --> 00:29:04.335
Let's do some together.

407
00:29:06.828 --> 00:29:09.672
- Two times four is?
- Eight.

408
00:29:09.831 --> 00:29:13.131
- Two times six is?
- Twelve.

409
00:29:13.502 --> 00:29:15.800
- Two times nine is?
- Eighteen.

410
00:29:15.963 --> 00:29:18.182
Excellent! You've
been practicing.

411
00:29:18.340 --> 00:29:20.684
Pretty soon you'll be able
to do any multiplication,

412
00:29:20.842 --> 00:29:23.436
- whether it's two times seven...
- Fourteen.

413
00:29:23.595 --> 00:29:27.190
Very good. Or 13 times 379.

414
00:29:27.349 --> 00:29:31.024
4927.

415
00:29:32.604 --> 00:29:34.356
I beg your pardon?

416
00:29:34.523 --> 00:29:36.867
I think that's the answer.

417
00:29:37.025 --> 00:29:40.370
13 times 379.

418
00:29:40.529 --> 00:29:42.031
4-9-2-7.

419
00:30:00.549 --> 00:30:02.222
It is.

420
00:30:03.051 --> 00:30:04.724
Wow.

421
00:30:08.348 --> 00:30:11.067
Matilda, you know how to
multiply big numbers?

422
00:30:11.685 --> 00:30:15.690
I read this book last year on
mathematics at the library.

423
00:30:17.983 --> 00:30:19.656
You like to read?

424
00:30:19.818 --> 00:30:22.071
Oh, yes, I love to read.

425
00:30:22.362 --> 00:30:23.830
What do you like to read?

426
00:30:25.699 --> 00:30:29.829
Everything, but lately I've
been reading Darles Chickens.

427
00:30:31.079 --> 00:30:34.879
Charles Dickens. I could
read him every day.

428
00:30:36.251 --> 00:30:38.094
So could I.

429
00:30:41.131 --> 00:30:42.474
All right, everyone,

430
00:30:42.632 --> 00:30:46.136
take out your workbooks and
let's start with section three.

431
00:30:54.102 --> 00:30:55.775
I'll be back in a moment.

432
00:31:08.325 --> 00:31:13.297
Yippee! Gotcha right
in the neck! And you. Woo-hoo!

433
00:31:13.455 --> 00:31:16.299
Yes! You... Come in, come
in, whoever you are.

434
00:31:20.128 --> 00:31:22.472
Almost got you.

435
00:31:23.090 --> 00:31:27.140
Good to see you, Jen.
Good, good, good.

436
00:31:27.302 --> 00:31:30.476
Time for one of our
little heart-to-hearts?

437
00:31:33.892 --> 00:31:37.362
Actually, it's about the new girl
in my class, Miss Trunchbull,

438
00:31:37.521 --> 00:31:39.148
Matilda Wormwood.

439
00:31:39.314 --> 00:31:42.158
Her father says she's
a real wart. A what?

440
00:31:42.317 --> 00:31:45.787
A carbuncle, a blister, a festering
pustule of malignant ooze.

441
00:31:45.946 --> 00:31:51.043
Oh, no, Matilda Wormwood is a
very sweet girl, and very bright.

442
00:31:51.201 --> 00:31:52.794
A bright child?

443
00:31:52.953 --> 00:31:55.251
Yes. She can multiply
large sums in her head.

444
00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:58.003
So can a calculator.

445
00:31:58.166 --> 00:32:03.764
Well, I think she might be happier
in an older and more advanced class.

446
00:32:03.922 --> 00:32:06.095
Ah, I knew it!

447
00:32:06.258 --> 00:32:08.073
You can't handle the little
viper, so you're trying

448
00:32:08.097 --> 00:32:09.933
to foist her off on one
of the other teachers.

449
00:32:10.095 --> 00:32:11.847
No, no, no, Miss Trunchbull.
Yes!

450
00:32:12.013 --> 00:32:14.687
Typical, slothful cowardice.

451
00:32:14.850 --> 00:32:17.194
Listen to me, Jen.

452
00:32:17.352 --> 00:32:21.983
The distance the shot put goes depends
upon the effort you put into it.

453
00:32:22.149 --> 00:32:23.651
Perspiration!

454
00:32:23.817 --> 00:32:28.163
If you can't handle the little
brat, I'll lock her in the choky!

455
00:32:30.740 --> 00:32:32.959
Get it? Yes, ma'am.

456
00:32:33.118 --> 00:32:37.715
One day, Jen, you'll see that
everything I do is for your own good,

457
00:32:37.873 --> 00:32:42.219
and the good of those
putrescent little children!

458
00:33:03.857 --> 00:33:06.235
Get back at Tiffany.
Before.

459
00:33:06.401 --> 00:33:08.403
When she was having that...
Mom, I'm home.

460
00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:11.619
How was school?
School was great.

461
00:33:11.781 --> 00:33:14.409
My teacher lets me do
sixth-grade work. Look.

462
00:33:14.576 --> 00:33:16.920
Algebra and geography.
Hold on a minute.

463
00:33:17.078 --> 00:33:19.797
Can't you see I'm in the middle
of an important phone call?

464
00:33:20.123 --> 00:33:22.376
Well, you just asked
me how school was.

465
00:33:22.542 --> 00:33:24.010
Quiet.

466
00:33:24.169 --> 00:33:26.592
What else was she supposed
to do? The baby wasn't his.

467
00:33:26.755 --> 00:33:29.099
Well, it was really great.

468
00:33:29.257 --> 00:33:31.806
No way. They gotta be implants.

469
00:33:31.968 --> 00:33:36.815
The principal is insane. She threw
a girl over the fence by her hair.

470
00:33:36.973 --> 00:33:40.853
It would change your life too if
you waxed yours, I'm positive.

471
00:33:41.019 --> 00:33:44.023
I have the most
wonderful teacher.

472
00:33:44.272 --> 00:33:46.115
Mine are driving me crazy.

473
00:33:46.274 --> 00:33:49.619
I'm telling you, six hours a
day at school is not enough.

474
00:33:49.778 --> 00:33:51.200
I'll say.

475
00:33:51.363 --> 00:33:54.913
Hiyah. Whack to the belly! A smack to
the face. Another smack to the face!

476
00:33:55.075 --> 00:33:57.235
Burns is hurt. He's on the
ropes, ladies and gentlemen.

477
00:33:58.203 --> 00:34:00.171
Saved by the bell.

478
00:34:00.539 --> 00:34:02.837
Packages at this hour?
Come here.

479
00:34:02.999 --> 00:34:05.548
What? Okay.

480
00:34:09.089 --> 00:34:10.136
Hello.

481
00:34:10.298 --> 00:34:14.223
We don't give money. We don't like
charities. We don't buy raffle tickets.

482
00:34:14.386 --> 00:34:16.309
Mr. Wormwood.

483
00:34:16.471 --> 00:34:18.644
I'm Jennifer Honey. I'm
Matilda's teacher.

484
00:34:18.807 --> 00:34:20.434
What has she done now?

485
00:34:20.600 --> 00:34:24.980
You! Go to your room right now!
Right now. Beat it!

486
00:34:25.438 --> 00:34:28.738
Look, whatever it is,
she's your problem now.

487
00:34:28.900 --> 00:34:30.823
No, there is no problem.

488
00:34:31.152 --> 00:34:33.405
Then beat it. We're watching TV.

489
00:34:34.990 --> 00:34:38.961
Mr. Wormwood, if you think
watching some rotten TV show

490
00:34:39.119 --> 00:34:42.464
is more important than your daughter,
then maybe you shouldn't be a parent.

491
00:34:42.622 --> 00:34:46.047
Now, why don't you turn that
darn thing off and listen to me?

492
00:34:50.213 --> 00:34:52.307
All right, come in.
Get this over with.

493
00:34:52.465 --> 00:34:55.685
Mrs. Wormwood's not gonna
like this. Come on, get in.

494
00:34:58.638 --> 00:34:59.685
Close the door.

495
00:34:59.848 --> 00:35:01.850
Who is it? Some teacher.

496
00:35:02.017 --> 00:35:04.861
Says she's gotta talk
to you about Matilda.

497
00:35:06.021 --> 00:35:09.321
What did you do that for? He
had Velasquez on the ropes.

498
00:35:09.733 --> 00:35:10.780
What do you want?

499
00:35:10.942 --> 00:35:14.412
I'm sure you're aware by now that
Matilda has a brilliant mind.

500
00:35:14.571 --> 00:35:16.448
Yeah, right. Mikey,
get me a beer.

501
00:35:16.615 --> 00:35:19.243
Her math skills are
simply extraordinary.

502
00:35:19.409 --> 00:35:21.503
She's reading material that I...
Want one?

503
00:35:21.661 --> 00:35:24.039
Oh, no, thank you, dear.

504
00:35:24.205 --> 00:35:28.506
Material that I didn't see until
my second year of college.

505
00:35:28.668 --> 00:35:30.716
Oh, college. Great, college.

506
00:35:30.879 --> 00:35:33.098
I really feel, with
private instruction

507
00:35:33.256 --> 00:35:36.055
that she'd be ready for college
in just a few short years.

508
00:35:36.217 --> 00:35:38.720
Look, Miss Snit.

509
00:35:38.887 --> 00:35:42.266
A girl does not get anywhere
by acting intelligent.

510
00:35:42.432 --> 00:35:44.400
I mean, take a look
at you and me.

511
00:35:44.809 --> 00:35:47.938
You chose books.
I chose looks.

512
00:35:48.104 --> 00:35:51.734
I have a nice house,
a wonderful husband,

513
00:35:51.900 --> 00:35:56.781
and you are slaving away teaching
snot-nosed children their ABC's.

514
00:35:56.946 --> 00:36:00.667
You want Matilda to go
to college? Ha-ha-ha.

515
00:36:00.867 --> 00:36:05.088
College! I didn't go to college.
I don't know anybody who did.

516
00:36:05.246 --> 00:36:08.796
Bunch of hippies and
cesspool salesmen. Ha-ha-ha.

517
00:36:08.958 --> 00:36:12.132
Don't sneer at educated
people, Mr. Wormwood.

518
00:36:12.295 --> 00:36:14.673
If you became ill,
heaven forbid,

519
00:36:14.839 --> 00:36:18.013
your doctor would be
a college graduate.

520
00:36:18.218 --> 00:36:21.142
Or say you were sued for
selling a faulty car.

521
00:36:21.304 --> 00:36:23.602
The lawyer who defended you
would've gone to college too.

522
00:36:23.765 --> 00:36:27.110
What car? Sued by who?

523
00:36:27.268 --> 00:36:30.397
Who you been talking to?
Nobody.

524
00:36:33.191 --> 00:36:38.914
Oh, dear, I can see we're
not going to agree, are we?

525
00:36:39.489 --> 00:36:42.743
No. I'm sorry I burst
in on you like this.

526
00:36:42.909 --> 00:36:44.627
Sorry.

527
00:36:46.037 --> 00:36:48.460
We ought to Sue her
for interrupting our show.

528
00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:50.883
Tell me about it.

529
00:36:51.292 --> 00:36:53.090
Why's he in the
middle of the ring?

530
00:36:53.253 --> 00:36:55.534
He's standing in the middle
of the ring because it's over.

531
00:36:55.588 --> 00:36:56.885
Thank you.

532
00:36:57.048 --> 00:36:58.728
We missed it?
Tomorrow.

533
00:36:58.883 --> 00:37:02.558
Great, it's over.
Who won?

534
00:37:02.721 --> 00:37:04.348
How do I know?
You shut it off!

535
00:37:04.514 --> 00:37:06.858
Was it my fault that she
came in the middle of the fight?

536
00:37:07.016 --> 00:37:08.563
Hop to.
Hippity-hop.

537
00:37:08.727 --> 00:37:13.324
The entire school will go to
the assembly room immediately.

538
00:37:13.481 --> 00:37:15.108
Sit!

539
00:37:16.151 --> 00:37:18.904
What's up? Beats me.

540
00:37:22.198 --> 00:37:24.496
Bruce Bogtrotter.

541
00:37:33.334 --> 00:37:36.713
Would little Brucey
come up here, please?

542
00:37:49.058 --> 00:37:51.686
He lives on my block.

543
00:37:56.357 --> 00:38:00.453
This boy, Bruce Bogtrotter,

544
00:38:00.612 --> 00:38:04.537
is none other than a
vicious sneak thief.

545
00:38:04.699 --> 00:38:07.043
You're a disgusting
criminal, aren't you?

546
00:38:07.202 --> 00:38:09.625
I don't know what
you're talking about.

547
00:38:09.788 --> 00:38:12.712
Cake. Chocolate cake.

548
00:38:13.082 --> 00:38:16.336
You slithered like a serpent
into the school kitchen

549
00:38:16.503 --> 00:38:18.881
and ate my personal snack!

550
00:38:19.506 --> 00:38:21.804
Do you deny it?

551
00:38:26.387 --> 00:38:29.231
Confess!

552
00:38:29.724 --> 00:38:32.978
Well, it's hard for me to
remember a specific cake.

553
00:38:33.728 --> 00:38:35.651
This one

554
00:38:35.814 --> 00:38:37.236
was mine.

555
00:38:37.398 --> 00:38:41.244
And it was the most scrumptious
cake in the entire world.

556
00:38:41.402 --> 00:38:42.528
My mom's is better.

557
00:38:44.155 --> 00:38:46.533
It is, is it?

558
00:38:46.741 --> 00:38:50.041
How can you be sure unless
you have another piece?

559
00:38:51.579 --> 00:38:54.549
Sit down, Bog.

560
00:39:12.100 --> 00:39:14.523
Here we go.

561
00:39:14.936 --> 00:39:18.156
Smells chocolaty, eh?

562
00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:22.284
Now, eat it!

563
00:39:24.904 --> 00:39:27.623
I don't want any, thank you.

564
00:39:28.366 --> 00:39:29.413
Eat it!

565
00:39:32.287 --> 00:39:34.085
Don't eat it.

566
00:39:34.873 --> 00:39:36.295
She wouldn't
give him cake.

567
00:39:36.457 --> 00:39:38.630
It's poison. Something's up.

568
00:39:45.216 --> 00:39:48.516
Mm. Mm-hm. Yeah.

569
00:40:09.574 --> 00:40:12.578
You look like you
enjoyed that, Brucey.

570
00:40:13.161 --> 00:40:14.663
Yes, ma'am.

571
00:40:14.996 --> 00:40:17.340
You must have some more.

572
00:40:18.124 --> 00:40:19.922
Oh, no, thanks.

573
00:40:20.084 --> 00:40:22.428
But you'll hurt Cook's feelings.

574
00:40:22.587 --> 00:40:24.681
Huh? Cookie.

575
00:40:27.800 --> 00:40:32.681
She made this cake just for
you to have on your very own.

576
00:40:35.266 --> 00:40:39.021
Her sweat and blood
went into this cake

577
00:40:39.187 --> 00:40:45.365
and you will not leave this platform until
you have consumed the entire confection!

578
00:40:45.526 --> 00:40:47.699
Entire confection.

579
00:40:48.071 --> 00:40:50.369
See you at lunch.
Thank you, Cookie.

580
00:40:50.531 --> 00:40:54.286
Rotten kids. You wanted
cake, you got cake.

581
00:40:54.452 --> 00:40:56.875
Now, eat it!

582
00:41:10.593 --> 00:41:12.721
Poor Brucey.

583
00:41:45.670 --> 00:41:47.718
He's going to puke.

584
00:41:48.589 --> 00:41:51.342
I can't look. Is
he going to puke?

585
00:41:51.509 --> 00:41:53.432
Without a doubt.

586
00:42:01.102 --> 00:42:02.775
Bruce looks real bad.

587
00:42:02.937 --> 00:42:05.110
Give up? Ha-ha-ha.

588
00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:12.033
You can do it, Brucey!

589
00:42:12.447 --> 00:42:14.700
You can do it, Bruce!

590
00:42:15.533 --> 00:42:16.910
Yeah, you can do it!

591
00:42:18.286 --> 00:42:20.630
Go, Bruce!

592
00:42:21.080 --> 00:42:22.957
Bruce! Bruce!
Bruce! Bruce! Bruce!

593
00:42:27.587 --> 00:42:28.634
Silence!

594
00:42:32.133 --> 00:42:33.726
Yes!

595
00:42:33.968 --> 00:42:36.096
Yeah!

596
00:42:37.764 --> 00:42:38.811
Silence!

597
00:42:42.894 --> 00:42:45.488
Stop! Silence!

598
00:43:08.836 --> 00:43:11.430
Shut up!
The entire assembly

599
00:43:11.589 --> 00:43:15.469
will stay five hours after school
and copy from the dictionary.

600
00:43:15.968 --> 00:43:19.643
Any children who object will
go straight into the choky

601
00:43:19.806 --> 00:43:21.683
together!

602
00:43:27.188 --> 00:43:30.818
MAN Rescue 8 out of
Station 8, Los Angeles County.

603
00:43:30.983 --> 00:43:35.079
This was a Code R, an official way
of saying we've caught a bad one.

604
00:43:35.238 --> 00:43:38.708
The kind of accident where death
itself holds a stopwatch on us.

605
00:43:41.244 --> 00:43:42.962
Young lady, where were you?

606
00:43:43.121 --> 00:43:46.441
Miss Trunchbull kept the whole school late
because this boy ate some chocolate cake.

607
00:43:46.541 --> 00:43:49.545
That's the biggest lie I ever heard.
You see those packages over there?

608
00:43:49.710 --> 00:43:52.964
They were left out for the world to see
because you weren't here to take them in.

609
00:43:53.131 --> 00:43:55.350
I don't think it's
fair, bumpkins. What?

610
00:43:55.508 --> 00:43:58.682
You get all this stuff from
catalogs, and I don't get anything.

611
00:43:58.845 --> 00:44:02.440
It's not catalogs, it's car
parts, sweetness. It's business.

612
00:44:02.598 --> 00:44:05.568
Oh, if it's business, why don't
you have it sent to the office?

613
00:44:05.726 --> 00:44:07.728
Because the cops may be
watching the office.

614
00:44:07.895 --> 00:44:10.148
The cops are
watching the house.

615
00:44:10.314 --> 00:44:13.409
What? They're parked
outside right now.

616
00:44:13.860 --> 00:44:15.908
You are such an ignoramus.

617
00:44:16.070 --> 00:44:20.075
Those are speedboat salesmen.
Really nice guys.

618
00:44:20.241 --> 00:44:21.914
Cops.

619
00:44:24.078 --> 00:44:27.503
Speedboats? There are
no lakes around here.

620
00:44:27.665 --> 00:44:31.135
Yeah, but some people like
to go away on the weekends.

621
00:44:31.294 --> 00:44:34.468
Some people have fun. And
some people are cops.

622
00:44:34.630 --> 00:44:36.598
They are not cops. Are too.

623
00:44:36.757 --> 00:44:39.277
They are not. I ought to know if
there's cops watching my house.

624
00:44:39.427 --> 00:44:42.431
Now, go to bed, you
lying little earwig.

625
00:44:43.890 --> 00:44:45.813
With the FBI
watching her father

626
00:44:45.975 --> 00:44:48.398
and the Trunchbull
terrorising her school,

627
00:44:48.561 --> 00:44:52.361
it was a rare, happy moment when Matilda
could just play with her friends.

628
00:44:52.523 --> 00:44:55.868
A frog! A frog! A frog!

629
00:44:56.736 --> 00:45:00.206
What is it, Lavender? A frog!

630
00:45:02.158 --> 00:45:03.375
It's a salamander.

631
00:45:03.534 --> 00:45:05.457
- It's a chameleon.
- It's a newt.

632
00:45:05.620 --> 00:45:10.091
"Any of the small semiaquatic
salamanders from the genus Triturus."

633
00:45:10.249 --> 00:45:14.880
"Some are brightly colored and
secrete irritating substances."

634
00:45:18.299 --> 00:45:20.597
How could
you keep going...?

635
00:45:20.760 --> 00:45:24.310
Useless, flaming car!

636
00:45:25.139 --> 00:45:26.561
Wormwood!

637
00:45:26.807 --> 00:45:28.400
Sell me a lemon?

638
00:45:28.559 --> 00:45:30.561
You're heading for the
choky, young lady!

639
00:45:30.728 --> 00:45:31.820
Choky? Teach you a lesson.

640
00:45:31.979 --> 00:45:33.105
What lesson?

641
00:45:33.272 --> 00:45:35.570
You and your father think you
can make a fool out of me!

642
00:45:35.733 --> 00:45:38.282
My father? The guy with
that stupid haircut!

643
00:45:38.611 --> 00:45:42.616
I'm nothing like my father.
You're the spitting image.

644
00:45:42.823 --> 00:45:45.872
The apple never rots
far from the tree.

645
00:45:46.994 --> 00:45:48.086
Miss Honey!

646
00:45:48.246 --> 00:45:50.374
Miss Trunchbull teaches our
class today, Lavender.

647
00:45:50.539 --> 00:45:52.184
Please get a water pitcher.
But Miss Honey...

648
00:45:52.208 --> 00:45:55.337
Shh, shh. Quickly. She'll be
here any second. Come on.

649
00:45:56.379 --> 00:46:00.179
Make sure the water's cold, Lavender.
Hurry. Vinnie, cover the fish.

650
00:46:00.841 --> 00:46:03.890
Put away the art projects.
Put away anything colorful.

651
00:46:04.053 --> 00:46:05.781
Oh, Charlie, won't you get
those crayons for me.

652
00:46:05.805 --> 00:46:09.480
Most great ideas come from
hard work and careful planning.

653
00:46:09.642 --> 00:46:13.363
Of course, once in a while,
they just jump out at you.

654
00:46:13.521 --> 00:46:16.149
Raina, cover the birds
and beetles. Hurry! Hurry!

655
00:46:16.315 --> 00:46:18.363
I hear her coming. Okay, now,

656
00:46:18.526 --> 00:46:21.245
last time, some of you
forgot yourselves.

657
00:46:21.404 --> 00:46:25.204
Don't speak unless you're spoken
to. Don't laugh. Don't smile.

658
00:46:25.366 --> 00:46:27.494
Don't even breathe loudly.

659
00:46:27.743 --> 00:46:30.212
Don't
breathe at all.

660
00:46:32.456 --> 00:46:34.049
Morning, Miss Trunchbull.

661
00:46:34.208 --> 00:46:36.427
Good morning,
Miss Trunchbull.

662
00:46:38.045 --> 00:46:39.171
Sit!

663
00:46:43.718 --> 00:46:45.686
Shoo!

664
00:46:48.014 --> 00:46:50.244
I have never
been able to understand

665
00:46:50.268 --> 00:46:52.520
why small children
are so disgusting.

666
00:46:52.685 --> 00:46:54.904
They're the bane of my life.

667
00:46:55.062 --> 00:46:57.485
They're like insects.
Where's Matilda?

668
00:46:57.648 --> 00:47:00.993
They should be got
rid of as early as possible.

669
00:47:01.277 --> 00:47:02.824
Fsht!

670
00:47:03.404 --> 00:47:05.577
My idea of a perfect school

671
00:47:05.740 --> 00:47:10.621
is one in which there
are no children at all.

672
00:47:11.746 --> 00:47:14.215
Do you agree, Miss Honey?

673
00:47:18.127 --> 00:47:19.219
Now,

674
00:47:19.879 --> 00:47:22.758
you, front of the class!

675
00:47:28.763 --> 00:47:30.936
Are you okay?

676
00:47:31.932 --> 00:47:33.957
Next time
I tell you to empty

677
00:47:33.981 --> 00:47:36.028
your pockets, you'll do
it faster, won't you?

678
00:47:36.187 --> 00:47:38.610
- Yes, Miss Trunchbull.
- Miss Honey.

679
00:47:39.148 --> 00:47:43.119
This could be the most interesting
thing you've ever done.

680
00:47:46.447 --> 00:47:49.041
Sit down, you squirming
worm of vomit!

681
00:47:49.200 --> 00:47:51.578
Thank you, Miss Trunchbull.

682
00:48:01.087 --> 00:48:02.805
Get up!

683
00:48:05.299 --> 00:48:06.346
Can you spell?

684
00:48:06.592 --> 00:48:09.687
Miss Honey taught us how to
spell a long word yesterday.

685
00:48:09.845 --> 00:48:11.597
We can spell "difficulty."

686
00:48:11.764 --> 00:48:15.485
You couldn't spell "difficulty"
if your life depended on it.

687
00:48:15.935 --> 00:48:17.687
She taught us with a poem.

688
00:48:17.853 --> 00:48:19.526
A poem, how sweet.

689
00:48:19.688 --> 00:48:25.115
What poem would that be?
Mrs. D, Mrs. I.

690
00:48:25.277 --> 00:48:27.746
Mrs. F-F-I.

691
00:48:27.905 --> 00:48:32.411
Mrs. C, Mrs. U Mrs. L-T-Y.

692
00:48:33.327 --> 00:48:35.500
Why are
all these women married?

693
00:48:35.663 --> 00:48:40.009
Mrs. D? Mrs. I? You're supposed to
be teaching spelling, not poetry!

694
00:48:45.756 --> 00:48:48.049
I cannot, for the life
of me, understand why

695
00:48:48.073 --> 00:48:50.387
small children take
so long to grow up.

696
00:48:50.553 --> 00:48:53.306
I think they do it
deliberately just to annoy me.

697
00:49:09.780 --> 00:49:11.953
What's funny? Hm?

698
00:49:12.199 --> 00:49:14.952
Come on, spit it out.
Speak up.

699
00:49:15.119 --> 00:49:18.043
I like a joke as well
as the next fat person.

700
00:49:23.586 --> 00:49:26.965
Ah! It's a snake. It's a snake!

701
00:49:27.965 --> 00:49:29.842
It's a snake! Uch!

702
00:49:31.844 --> 00:49:35.269
One of you tried to poison me.
Who?

703
00:49:36.557 --> 00:49:38.559
Matilda.

704
00:49:38.726 --> 00:49:39.773
I knew it!

705
00:49:40.019 --> 00:49:43.740
I just thought you'd like to know,
it's not a snake. It's a newt.

706
00:49:43.898 --> 00:49:46.868
What did you say? It's a newt.

707
00:49:47.026 --> 00:49:52.248
Stand up, you villainous sack
of goat slime! You did this.

708
00:49:52.406 --> 00:49:53.532
No, Miss Trunchbull.

709
00:49:53.699 --> 00:49:58.205
Did you act alone, or did
you have accomplices?

710
00:49:58.370 --> 00:49:59.997
I didn't do it.

711
00:50:00.164 --> 00:50:02.587
You didn't like the
choky, did you?

712
00:50:02.750 --> 00:50:04.844
Thought you'd pay me
back, didn't you?

713
00:50:05.002 --> 00:50:08.131
Well, I'll pay you
back, young lady.

714
00:50:08.297 --> 00:50:11.346
For what, Miss Trunchbull? For
this newt, you piss-worm!

715
00:50:11.509 --> 00:50:14.433
I'm telling you, I didn't do it!

716
00:50:15.095 --> 00:50:17.518
Besides, even if you didn't
do it, I'm gonna punish you

717
00:50:17.681 --> 00:50:21.436
because I'm big and you're small,
and I'm right and you're wrong.

718
00:50:21.602 --> 00:50:24.196
And there's nothing
you can do about it.

719
00:50:24.355 --> 00:50:28.280
You're a liar and a scoundrel, and
your father's a liar and a cheat.

720
00:50:28.442 --> 00:50:32.948
You're the most corrupt lowlifes
in the history of civilization.

721
00:50:33.113 --> 00:50:35.616
Am I wrong'? I'm never wrong.

722
00:50:36.242 --> 00:50:42.124
In this classroom, in
this school, I am God!

723
00:51:13.779 --> 00:51:15.497
You! I didn't move.

724
00:51:16.156 --> 00:51:17.703
You did this!

725
00:51:17.866 --> 00:51:21.996
How could she possibly have done it
when she was sitting way over here?

726
00:51:23.080 --> 00:51:26.550
I'll be watching you,
each and every one.

727
00:51:26.709 --> 00:51:28.382
When you turn the corner,

728
00:51:28.544 --> 00:51:31.673
when you go to your cubbies
to get your smelly coats,

729
00:51:31.839 --> 00:51:33.841
when you skip merrily to lunch,

730
00:51:34.008 --> 00:51:36.852
I'll be watching
you, all of you,

731
00:51:37.011 --> 00:51:39.560
and especially you.

732
00:51:48.814 --> 00:51:50.657
Oh, sweetheart, I'm sorry.

